Black transposes into the Taimanov line, but most probably his main reason for this move is to free his bishop for an attack. On gameknot the line is still called Sicilian (B32), Flohr variation.
Black transposes into the Taimanov line, but most probably his main reason for this move is to free his bishop for an attack. On gameknot the line is still called Sicilian (B32), Flohr variation.
White doesn't know that line, so he makes an automatic move thinking that he seriously pins the knight. The Taimanov line continues with 5. Nxc6.
Black believes in his queen's power, and loves to mobilize her early.

Here white completely neglects the position, and makes another automatic move without consideration to the threats. The knight on d4 is extremely weak, and does more harm than good in this position. The bishop on b5 would probably serve better if he exchanged at c6.
Black opts for an unjustified fianchetto, and gives back time to  white.
White keeps neglecting the essence of the position, and hopes that this will protect his bishop or he simply wants to develop another piece. Now his knight on d4 is hopelessly hanged.
Fortunately black is equally in haste, so he rushes away and misses the free capture of White's knight.
White misses the given and time-winning fork on a4, and invites to battle for the dominance of d4.
Confusing move, and that's probably the scope here. White wants to break Black's psychological dominance, and make him stop and wonder.

Another lame attack, and without positional care.
Another lame attack, and without positional care.
Now black feels like a King on the board, and he is completely sure of winning this game. Who wouldn't, given this hopeless situation for white ?
White keeps fighting, knowing that blitz-games can turn around quickly.
Better would have been to defend with Qd3.
Better would have been to defend with Qd3.
Black feels like a Grandmaster now, and white is definitely losing here. But white knows that black is a rookie like himself, so he keeps hoping for mistakes on black's behalf.
What about the poor guy on c2 ?
What about the poor guy on c2 ?
What about the poor guy on c2 ?
Black doesn't care about pawns either, so what's next ?
White is too kind, and lets the hung knight on f6 live. He can't afford to miss material gaining opportunities like this.
At this point anything for white is losing, so he might as well start to swindle.
